\section*{\centerline{Abstract}}

Once an infectious disease reaches a period of stability within a population, its epidemiology is typically amenable to linear modeling. However, during periods of transition, behavior of infectious diseases is non-linear and therefore not conducive to linear analysis. When transition periods can be identified and are short enough, disease patterns outside of transition periods can typically still be analyzed using linear models. However, when transition periods predominate --- such as with sporadic or seasonal disease outbreaks --- linear modeling is not sufficient to produce robust estimates of disease patterns. For our ongoing work on respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) seasonality, we developed a method for estimating outcomes of seasonal and sporadic infectious disease outbreaks using multivariate sampling of a generalized additive model (GAM) with penalized basis splines (P-splines). Our approach to RSV generalizes to other systems dominated by non-linear behavior, including other seasonal infections. Here we present our general approach, its application to RSV, and an R package that provides a convenient interface for conducting and validating this type of analysis in other areas.

